thread.title: $A bounces following jobs figures

title: $A bounces following jobs figures
text:
Thu, Sep 10, 2015, 12:56 PM AEST - Australia Markets close in 3 hrs 4 mins $A bounces following jobs figures AAP â€“ 10 minutes ago Print 
The Australian dollar is pushing its way back up towards 70 US cents, thanks to the release of some strong jobs figures. 
At 1200 AEST on Thursday, the currency was trading at 69.91 US cents, down from 70.49 cents on Wednesday. 
Earlier in the morning the currency fell as low as 69.46 US cents, after the Reserve Bank of New Zealand cut its interest rate, citing weaker economic growth. 
But the currency bounced after the latest employment figures showed that unemployment fell to 6.2 per cent in August and that there was another strong month of jobs growth, with the total number of people with jobs up 17,400. 
NAB senior economist David de Garis said the figures were solid and in line with "a pretty consistent picture of employment growth over the past few months". 
"(Monthly) employment growth of two per cent is more than respectable when the resources sector and allied industries have been laying off people," he said. 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* 69.91 US cents, from 70.49 cents on Wednesday 
* 84.11 Japanese yen, from 84.98 yen 
* 62.32 euro cents, from 63.20 euro cents 
* 111.45 New Zealand cents, from 110.62 NZ cents 
* 45.52 British pence, from 45.86 pence 
Government bond yields: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.819pct, from 1.831pct on Wednesday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.772pct, from 2.813pct 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* The September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.268 (implying a yield of 2.372 per cent), up from 97.233 (2.767 per cent) on Wednesday. 
* The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.140 (1.860 per cent), up from 98.135 (1.865 per cent). 
(*Currency closes taken at 1700 AEST previous local session, bond market closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
